Note:
PERSISTENT LIST - Immutable Cons-Cell List Tier 0 Primitive

This file implements a singly-linked cons-cell list designed for
functional (persistent) use. Every "modifying" operation returns a
new list that structurally shares its tail with the old list. The
old list remains valid - readers from a previous snapshot see the
old data.

Cons cell (24 bytes):
  offset 0:  value (8 bytes)
  offset 8:  tail (8 bytes; pointer to cdr)
  offset 16: refcount (8 bytes; atomic refcount for memory reclamation)

The empty list is represented by the pointer 0 (nil).

Because cells are shared, freeing must be reference-counted: cons()
takes ownership of one share of 'tail' and stores it; head/tail
accessors are reads only and do not retain; the destroy function
decrements the refcount and only frees when it reaches zero.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory

Let PLIST_CELL_SIZE be 24

@Reasoning
Construct a new cons cell with given head and tail. Increments the
refcount of the tail since the new cell now holds one share.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Allocate 24 bytes.
2) Store value at offset 0, tail at offset 8, refcount = 1 at offset 16.
3) If tail != 0, increment tail's refcount.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: 24 bytes.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "plist_cons" takes value as Integer, tail as Integer returns Integer:
    Let cell be proc allocate from Layout with PLIST_CELL_SIZE
    If cell is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with cell, 0, value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with cell, 8, tail
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with cell, 16, 1
    If tail is not equal to 0:
        Let rc be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tail, 16
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tail, 16, rc plus 1
    End If
    Return cell
End Process

@Reasoning
The empty list (nil) sentinel value.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 0 to indicate the empty list. Helper to keep the API uniform
with cons/head/tail.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "plist_nil" returns Integer:
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Empty predicate.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 1 if list pointer is 0.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "plist_is_empty" takes list as Integer returns Integer:
    If list is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
First element. Convention: head(nil) = 0 (the caller must check
is_empty first if 0 is a valid element).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Read offset 0 of cell.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "plist_head" takes list as Integer returns Integer:
    If list is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with list, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Tail of the list (everything after the first element).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Read offset 8 of cell. Tail of nil is nil.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "plist_tail" takes list as Integer returns Integer:
    If list is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with list, 8
End Process

@Reasoning
Length (number of elements). Walks the chain.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Iterate cdr-pointers counting cells.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "plist_length" takes list as Integer returns Integer:
    Let len be 0
    Let cur be list
    While cur is not equal to 0:
        Set len to len plus 1
        Set cur to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, 8
    End While
    Return len
End Process

@Reasoning
Retain - increment the refcount. Used when the caller wants to keep
a copy of the list pointer across an ownership boundary.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Bump the refcount at offset 16.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller must pair every retain with one release.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "plist_retain" takes list as Integer returns Integer:
    If list is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rc be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with list, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with list, 16, rc plus 1
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Release - decrement refcount. When it reaches zero, free the cell and
recurse into its tail.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Iterative release to avoid recursion-depth stack pressure on long
lists. While list is non-zero:
- Decrement refcount.
- If now zero, save tail, free this cell, advance to tail (which we
  then process with the same logic on the next iteration).
- If still > 0, stop because the tail is shared with another holder.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n) worst case if the list is unique. O(1) if shared.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller must not access list after release.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "plist_release" takes list as Integer returns Integer:
    Let cur be list
    While cur is not equal to 0:
        Let rc be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, 16
        Let new_rc be rc minus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with cur, 16, new_rc
        If new_rc is greater than 0:
            Return 1
        End If
        Let next_tail be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, 8
        proc deallocate from Layout with cur
        Set cur to next_tail
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Reverse a persistent list non-destructively. Builds a new list one
cons at a time; the old list remains valid.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Iterate the source list, consing each value onto an accumulator
initialized to nil. The result is reversed.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n). Space: O(n) for the new cells.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller must release the returned list when done.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "plist_reverse" takes list as Integer returns Integer:
    Let acc be 0
    Let cur be list
    While cur is not equal to 0:
        Let v be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, 0
        Let next be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, 8
        Let new_cell be proc plist_cons with v, acc
        If new_cell is equal to 0:
            proc plist_release with acc
            Return 0
        End If
        Note: plist_cons retained 'acc' once; the old acc reference we
        Note: held has been transferred into the new cell's tail slot,
        Note: so we drop our local reference (offset by the retain inside
        Note: cons we don't need to release here).
        Set acc to new_cell
        Set cur to next
    End While
    Return acc
End Process

@Reasoning
Append two persistent lists. Returns a new list whose elements are
a followed by b. b is shared (refcounted), a is copied cell-by-cell.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reverse(a) then cons each element onto b. Equivalent to:
  result = b; for each element of reverse(a): result = cons(element, result).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(|a|). Space: O(|a|) for the new cells.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller must release the returned list.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "plist_append" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ra be proc plist_reverse with a
    If ra is equal to 0:
        If a is equal to 0:
            proc plist_retain with b
            Return b
        End If
        Return 0
    End If
    Let result be b
    If b is not equal to 0:
        proc plist_retain with b
    End If
    Let cur be ra
    While cur is not equal to 0:
        Let v be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, 0
        Let new_cell be proc plist_cons with v, result
        If new_cell is equal to 0:
            proc plist_release with result
            proc plist_release with ra
            Return 0
        End If
        Note: cons retains 'result' for the new cell, so we release our
        Note: local reference to keep refcount accurate.
        proc plist_release with result
        Set result to new_cell
        Set cur to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, 8
    End While
    proc plist_release with ra
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
nth element accessor.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Walk n cells; return head of the nth, or 0 if shorter.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Out-of-range returns 0.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "plist_nth" takes list as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    If list is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If n is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let cur be list
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than n:
        If cur is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set cur to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, 8
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    If cur is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Refcount accessor for introspection / testing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Read offset 16.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "plist_refcount" takes list as Integer returns Integer:
    If list is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with list, 16
End Process
